## 19.2 Opening Files



Use the **open()** function to open a file:
# Open a file for reading

file = open("example.txt", "r")



# Do something with the file...



# Always close the file when done!

file.close()
### File Modes



| Mode | Description |

|------|-------------|

| **"r"** | Read (default) - file must exist |

| **"w"** | Write - creates new file or overwrites existing |

| **"a"** | Append - adds to end of existing file |

| **"x"** | Create - creates new file, fails if exists |

| **"r+"** | Read and write |



---
## 19.3 Reading Files
### Reading Entire File
# Read all content at once

file = open("example.txt", "r")

content = file.read()

print(content)

file.close()
### Reading Line by Line
# Read one line at a time

file = open("example.txt", "r")

for line in file:

    print(line.strip())  # strip() removes newline characters

file.close()
### Reading Lines into a List
# Read all lines into a list

file = open("example.txt", "r")

lines = file.readlines()

file.close()



print(lines)  # List of strings, each ending with \n
---



## Writing Files
### Writing Text
# Write to a file (overwrites existing content!)

file = open("output.txt", "w")

file.write("Hello, World!\n")

file.write("This is a new line.\n")

file.close()
# Write multiple lines at once

lines = ["First line\n", "Second line\n", "Third line\n"]

file = open("output.txt", "w")

file.writelines(lines)

file.close()
---



## 19.5 Appending to Files
# Add content to end of file (doesn't overwrite!)

file = open("log.txt", "a")

file.write("New log entry\n")

file.close()
---



## Context Managers (with statement)



The **with** statement automatically closes files:
# Better way - file closes automatically!

with open("example.txt", "r") as file:

    content = file.read()

    print(content)

# File is automatically closed here
### Why Use 'with'?



âœ… **Automatic cleanup** - file always closes

âœ… **Safer** - handles errors better

âœ… **Cleaner code** - no need to call close()



**Always prefer using 'with' for file operations!**



---
## 19.7 Practical Examples
# Example 1: Create a simple text file

with open("shopping_list.txt", "w") as file:

    file.write("Apples\n")

    file.write("Bananas\n")

    file.write("Milk\n")

    file.write("Bread\n")



print("Shopping list created!")
# Example 2: Read and display file contents

with open("shopping_list.txt", "r") as file:

    print("Shopping List:")

    print("-" * 20)

    for item in file:

        print(f"- {item.strip()}")
# Example 3: Count lines in a file

with open("shopping_list.txt", "r") as file:

    lines = file.readlines()

    print(f"Number of items: {len(lines)}")
# Example 4: Create a log file

import datetime



with open("activity_log.txt", "a") as file:

    timestamp = datetime.datetime.now()

    file.write(f"[{timestamp}] User logged in\n")



print("Log entry added!")
# Example 5: Read and process file

# Create a file with numbers

with open("numbers.txt", "w") as file:

    file.write("10\n20\n30\n40\n50\n")



# Read and calculate sum

total = 0

with open("numbers.txt", "r") as file:

    for line in file:

        number = int(line.strip())

        total += number



print(f"Sum of numbers: {total}")
